# Findings suppressed for the LOCAL working-tree scan (`npm run secret-scan`).
#
# `npm run secret-scan` runs with --no-git, which walks the filesystem and so
# reads .env / .env.local even though both are gitignored. Those files hold real
# credentials by design — that is what a .env IS. Without these entries the
# local scan fires on every run and everyone learns to ignore its output.
#
# SCOPE — read before adding anything here, and before moving this file:
#
# This file lives in `.gitleaks-local/` and is loaded ONLY by the local scan,
# via `-i .gitleaks-local` in the `secret-scan` script. That directory scoping is
# load-bearing. Gitleaks matches these fingerprints by SUFFIX, so the entry
# `.env:nextauth-secret:7` ALSO matches the history finding
# `3855042e…:.env:nextauth-secret:7`. If this file sits at the repo root where
# gitleaks auto-discovers it, it silences the ONB-01 history findings too — I
# verified that: the history scan dropped from 16 findings to "no leaks found".
#
# So: `secret-scan:history` passes `-i /dev/null` to load no ignore file at all,
# and CI's secret-scan-history job runs gitleaks directly without `-i`. Both
# still report the ONB-01 leak in full — 16 findings across commits 2a6c4c1a and
# 3855042e. Do not move this file to the repo root.
#
# This is the narrow version of what .gitleaks.toml used to do with a blanket
# `.env` path allowlist. That allowlist applied to history scans too and reported
# "no leaks found" on a repo with three live public credentials. Suppress
# specific known findings here; never re-add a path allowlist for .env.
#
# If a NEW secret is added to a new line of .env, its fingerprint won't match
# these and the scan will correctly fire.

.env:nextauth-secret:7
.env:newsapi-key:13
.env:gcp-api-key:16
.env:gemini-api-key-assignment:16
.env.local:nextauth-secret:7
.env.local:newsapi-key:13
.env.local:gcp-api-key:16
.env.local:gemini-api-key-assignment:16

# Added 2026-07-17 after rotating NEXTAUTH_SECRET and GEMINI_API_KEY. The
# replacement Gemini key matches `generic-api-key` (a broader default rule)
# where the old value matched `gcp-api-key`, so the local scan surfaced it as a
# new finding. Same file, same line, same purpose — a real key in a real,
# gitignored .env. Suppressed on the same grounds as the entries above.
.env:generic-api-key:16
